  "prompt": "Why doesn't my shift key work? How do I fix it?",
  "response": "Okay, let's troubleshoot why your shift key isn't working. There are several potential causes, and we'll go through them step-by-step.\n\n**1. Check the Obvious:**\n\n*   **Is it just *one* shift key, or both?**  If only one is malfunctioning, that narrows down the possibilities.\n*   **Try a different keyboard:** If you have a spare keyboard, plug it in and see if the shift keys work on that one. This will immediately tell you if the problem is with the keyboard itself or with your computer's software/settings.\n*   **Check the physical key:**  Make sure the key isn't physically stuck or obstructed.  Sometimes crumbs, dust, or other debris can get under the key and prevent it from pressing down properly.  Try gently wiggling the key and see if that helps.\n\n**2. Software/Settings Issues:**\n\n*   **Sticky Keys:** This is a common culprit.  Sticky Keys is an accessibility feature that locks modifier keys (like Shift, Ctrl, Alt) so you don't have to hold them down.  It's often activated accidentally.\n\n    *   **Windows:**\n        *   Press the Shift key **five times rapidly**. A Sticky Keys dialog box might appear. Click \"No\" to disable it.\n        *   Alternatively, go to:\n            *   **Windows 10/11:**  Settings > Accessibility > Keyboard. Make sure \"Sticky Keys\" is turned **off**.\n            *   **Windows 7:** Control Panel > Ease of Access Center > Make the keyboard easier to use. Uncheck the box next to \"Turn on Sticky Keys.\"\n    *   **macOS:**\n        *   Go to: System Preferences > Accessibility > Keyboard.\n        *   Click \"Hardware\".\n        *   Make sure \"Sticky Keys\" is turned **off**. You might also see an \"Options\" button next to Sticky Keys. Click it and ensure that \"Press the Shift key five times to turn Sticky Keys on or off\" is **unchecked** if you want to prevent accidental activation.\n\n*   **Filter Keys:**  Another accessibility feature that can cause problems.  Filter Keys ignores brief or repeated keystrokes, which could make it seem like the Shift key isn't working.\n\n    *   **Windows:**\n        *   **Windows 10/11:** Settings > Accessibility > Keyboard. Make sure \"Filter Keys\" is turned **off**.\n        *   **Windows 7:** Control Panel > Ease of Access Center > Make the keyboard easier to use.  Uncheck the box next to \"Turn on Filter Keys.\"\n\n*   **Keyboard Layout:**  Sometimes, the wrong keyboard layout is selected.  This is more likely to affect special characters, but it's worth checking.\n\n    *   **Windows:**\n        *   Settings > Time & Language > Language > Keyboard. Make sure the correct keyboard layout is selected. If you have multiple languages installed, ensure the correct one is active.\n    *   **macOS:**\n        *   System Preferences > Keyboard > Input Sources.  Make sure the correct keyboard layout is selected.\n\n*   **Driver Issues:**  A corrupted or outdated keyboard driver *could* be the problem, although it's less likely than Sticky Keys.\n\n    *   **Windows:**\n        *   Press the Windows key + X, then select \"Device Manager.\"\n        *   Expand \"Keyboards.\"\n        *   Right-click on your keyboard and select \"Update driver.\" Choose \"Search automatically for drivers.\"\n        *   If that doesn't work, try uninstalling the driver (right-click > Uninstall device) and then restarting your computer. Windows will usually reinstall the driver automatically.\n\n*   **Specific Application Issues:**  Does the shift key work in *some* programs but not others? If so, the problem might be with the application's settings or a conflict with another program. Check the application's settings for keyboard shortcuts or accessibility options.\n\n*   **Background Processes:** Rarely, a background program might be interfering with keyboard input. Try a clean boot to see if the problem goes away:\n\n    *   **Windows:** Search for \"msconfig\" in the Start menu and run System Configuration. On the \"Services\" tab, check \"Hide all Microsoft services\" and then click \"Disable all.\" On the \"Startup\" tab, click \"Open Task Manager\" and disable all startup items. Restart your computer. If the shift key works now, a background program was the culprit. You can then re-enable services and startup items one by one to find the problematic program.\n    *   **macOS:**  Restart your Mac in Safe Mode (hold down the Shift key while it's booting). This disables many third-party extensions and startup items. If the shift key works in Safe Mode, you know a third-party program is the issue.\n\n**3. Hardware Issues (if the above steps don't work):**\n\n*   **Dirty Keyboard:** As mentioned earlier, debris can prevent keys from working properly.  Try cleaning your keyboard thoroughly.  Turn off your computer and unplug the keyboard. Use compressed air to blow out any dust or crumbs. You can also use a slightly damp (not wet!) cloth to wipe down the keys.\n*   **Keyboard Damage:**  If you've spilled liquid on your keyboard or it's been physically damaged, the shift keys (or the keyboard as a whole) might be broken. In this case, you'll likely need to replace the keyboard.\n*   **Internal Keyboard Connector (Laptops):** For laptops, the ribbon cable connecting the keyboard to the motherboard might be loose or damaged. This is a more complex repair and usually requires a professional.\n\n**Troubleshooting Steps - Summarized and Ordered:**\n\n1.  **Basic Checks:**\n    *   Is it one or both shift keys?\n    *   Try a different keyboard.\n    *   Check for physical obstructions.\n2.  **Sticky Keys:** Disable it (press Shift 5 times, or go through Settings/System Preferences).\n3.  **Filter Keys:** Disable it (through Settings/System Preferences).\n4.  **Keyboard Layout:**  Verify the correct layout is selected.\n5.  **Driver Update/Reinstall:** Update or reinstall the keyboard driver.\n6.  **Application-Specific Issue:** Test in multiple programs; check problematic program's settings.\n7.  **Clean Boot:** Try a clean boot to rule out software conflicts.\n8.  **Clean the Keyboard:** Use compressed air and a slightly damp cloth.\n9.  **Hardware Damage:** Inspect for spills or physical damage. (Replace keyboard if necessary).\n10. **Laptop Keyboard Connector:** (Laptop only) Consider a professional repair.\n\n**When Asking for Further Help:**\n\nIf none of these steps work, and you need more help, please provide the following information:\n\n*   **Operating System:** (Windows 10, macOS Monterey, etc.)\n*   **Keyboard Type:** (Built-in laptop keyboard, USB keyboard, Bluetooth keyboard, brand and model if possible)\n*   **What you've already tried:** Be specific about which of the above steps you've already taken.\n*   **Specific Symptoms:** Is it intermittent? Does it only happen in certain programs?\n\nGood luck!  Let me know how it goes.\n",
